a, Slovenia, and Croatia it is also found (in Slovenia almost exclusively) in the Slavicized form   Gros   (see also 3 below). The Jewish name has been Hebraicized as   Gadol  .","English: descriptive nickname for a big man, from Middle English <i>gros</i>, <i>grosse</i>, <i>groce</i> ’large; heavy’, also meaning ‘simple, plain’, from Old French <i>gros</i> ‘big, fat’ (from Latin <i>grossus</i> ‘thick’), a word of ancient Germanic origin, thus etymologically the same word as in 1 above.","Germanized or Americanized form of Slovenian, Polish, Croatian or other Slavic   Gros  , itself of German origin (see 1 above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Gadol","meanings":["(2010: NA)","Jewish: Hebraicized form of   Gross   1, based on Hebrew <i>gadol</i> ‘large’."]},{"name":"Grohs","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Detlef, Florian, Gerhard, Hans, Heinz, Helmut, Kurt, Lothar, Otto.","German: variant of   Gross  .","Altered form of German   Groh  , with the addition of excrescent <i>-s</i>, a common feature of Americanized surnames."]},{"name":"Grossmann","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Dieter, Erwin, Hans, Kurt, Otto, Franz, Goetz, Gottlieb, Gunter, Heinz, Helmut, Horst.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): descriptive nickname for a large man, from <i>gross</i> ‘large’ (see   Gross  ) + <i>Mann</i> ‘man’."]},{"name":"Grosse","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Bernd, Eberhard, Erwin, Gerhard, Gerhardt, Hans, Hermann, Ingo, Otto, Reinhold, Uwe.","German and English: variant of   Gross  ."]},{"name":"Grosser","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Alois, Bernhard, Christoph, Ernst, Gunther, Siegfried, Wolf.","German:","nickname for a big man, from an inflected form of   Gross  ."]},{"name":"Groos","meanings":["German, Dutch, and English (of Norman origin): variant of   Gross  ."]},{"name":"Groce","meanings":["English (Cornwall, of Norman origin): variant of   Gross  .","Altered form of German   Gross  ."]},{"name":"Grote","meanings":["North German: nickname for a large man, from Low German <i>grot(h)</i> ‘large, corpulent’. Compare   Gross   and   Groth  .","Dutch: variant of   Groot  , a cognate of 1 above.","English: nickname from Middle English <i>grot</i> ‘groat, a denomination of coin’, from Middle Dutch <i>groot</i> ‘great’, being an elliptical use of the adjective, i.e. ‘thick (coin)’. In English use, from the 14th to 17th centuries, a groat was a silver coin equivalent to four pence."]},{"name":"Gros","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Emile, Camile, Albon, Alcide, Arsene, Chantelle, Clovis, Elphege, Etienne, Francois, Gabrielle.","French: nickname for a large or fat man, from Old French <i>gros</i> ‘big, fat’, from Late Latin <i>grossus</i>, of ancient Germanic origin. Compare   Legros  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic) and English (Middlesex, of Norman origin): variant of   Gross  ."]},{"name":"Grossett","meanings":["English and Scottish: nickname from a diminutive or pet form of Middle English <i>gros</i> ‘big; heavy’, also used to mean ‘plain and simple’ (Old French <i>gros</i> ‘big, fat’; see   Gross  ). This surname is frequent in Jamaica."]}]},{"name":"Ann","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Anne .  In the U.S. <i>Ann</i> is the more frequent spelling."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Le","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  ♂ ‘Profit’ or ‘sharp’.","2  ♀, ♂ ‘Upright’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Ann Le Gross was born in 1222, in Linton, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Eustace LeGrosse. She married Robert de Whitney in 1240, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1257, in Whitney-on-Wye, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 35."},"et":{"1222–1257":"1222–1257",